CaseSummary.Summary: Vehicle one (V1 - case vehicle), a 1999 Ford Taurus, 4-door sedan was traveling east in the eastbound lane of a two-lane, two-way roadway. Vehicle two (V2), a 2002 Chevrolet Tahoe, 4-door utility vehicle was stopped at an angle, blocking the eastbound traffic lane. V2 is a marked police vehicle that had its overhead lights operating and the driver was out of the vehicle assisting other officers clear a previous crash. It was dark, the sky was clear, and the bituminous road was dry. The driver of V1 failed to completely clear the frost from her windshield and had a limited vision of the road. The driver of V1 did not see V2 and the front of V1 struck the right side of V2 in a T-type configuration. Both vehicles were towed due to disabling vehicle damage. The 66-year-old female driver of V1 (case occupant) was not using the available three-point seat belt and the steering-wheel airbag deployed. She was transported via ground ambulance to a local hosptial and later transferred to a regional level-one trauma center.

CirenCaseForm.InjuryAnalysis:
The case occupant is the 163 cm (5' 4"), 110 kg (244 lb), 66-year-old female driver of a 1999 Ford Taurus, 4-door sedan. The case vehicle struck the right side of a stopped 2002 Chevrolet Tahoe, 4-door utility vehicle. The struck vehicle was a marked police vehicle and was stopped at an angle blocking the travel lane while police cleared a previous crash scene. The case occupant did not see the other vehicle (with its overhead lights activated) due to frost on the windshield. The impact was classified as moderate. The WinSmash program calculated a delta-v of 25 kmph (16 mph), which appeared to be consistent with the observed damage. The case occupant was not using the available three-point seat belt. The steering wheel airbag deployed.
In response to the 12 o'clock direction of force, she moved forward, relative to the vehicle interior. She sustained a left posterior acetabular fracture with dislocation of the femoral head and left sciatic nerve palsy from contact with the knee bolster.
